# Files autoformat and autolint should skip.
#
# Each non-comment non-blank line is a bash glob pattern (supports
# `*`, `?`, `[...]`; no `**`, no negations) matched against the file
# path passed to autoformat/autolint. A match → the script exits 0
# without running any tool.
#
# This file is read by both autoformat and autolint — autoformat's
# AUTOFORMAT_DIR and autolint's AUTOLINT_DIR both default to
# ~/.config/autoformat/, so one file covers both.

# karabiner-elements owns this file — reformatting it means the app
# will just rewrite on next save, producing churn and noise diffs.
*/karabiner.json

# Generated by `mise lock`; contains per-platform checksums + URLs in
# a specific order. Running taplo over it re-emits differently and
# would churn on every lockfile refresh.
*/mise.lock

# iTerm2 dynamic-profile file — iTerm reads this to configure the
# terminal. Reformatting could change key order in ways iTerm
# doesn't like.
*/iterm2-dotfiles-dyn-profile.json

# biome can't format its own config cleanly: when cwd is $HOME
# (common when invoking autoformat), biome treats $HOME as an
# implicit root and flags this file as a "nested root". The self-
# format guard on --config-path isn't enough to suppress that
# discovery path. The file is user-edited config, small — safe
# to skip.
*/autoformat/biome.json

# nvim lua files heavily use the `vim` global (neovim's scripting
# API). Our fallback `selene.toml` doesn't declare a nvim std, so
# `selene` flags every vim.* reference as undefined_variable,
# producing hundreds of false-positives per file. Ignoring here
# silences both autoformat and autolint for the nvim config;
# proper fix is a nvim-specific `selene.toml` with a vim std
# file, tracked as a follow-up.
*/.config/nvim/*

# Managed by Claude Code and Codex CLI — both tools rewrite these
# files (settings / config) on their own schedule, so any format
# we impose gets clobbered on next tool startup.
*/.claude/settings.json
*/.codex/config.toml

# Claude Code slash-command files: structured markdown with a
# YAML front-matter-like metadata block that rumdl's MD041 flags
# ("first line in file should be a level 1 heading"). The shape
# is intentional and mirrors how Claude parses them; formatting
# would be cosmetic and the lint noise isn't actionable.
*/.claude/commands/*
